04547nam a22008535i 9780814723081DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20032003nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780814723081  a(DE-B1597)547422  a(OCoLC)58844215  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHV9470b.B75 2003eb 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a365/.023/732221 aBritton, Dana M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAt Work in the Iron Cage :bThe Prison as Gendered Organization /cDana M. Britton. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Engendering the Prison -- t2. Penology in America Men’s and Women’s Prisons as Gendered Projects -- t3. From Turnkey to Officer -- t4. Paths to Prison -- t5. Work with Inmates -- t6. The Rest of the Job -- t7. Conclusion -- tMethodological Appendix -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen most people think of prisons, they imagine chaos, violence, and fundamentally, an atmosphere of overwhelming brute masculinity. But real prisons rarely fit the “Big House” stereotype of popular film and literature. One fifth of all correctional officers are women, and the rate at which women are imprisoned is growing faster than that of men. Yet, despite increasing numbers of women prisoners and officers, ideas about prison life and prison work are sill dominated by an exaggerated image of men’s prisons where inmates supposedly struggle for physical dominance.In a rare comparative analysis of men’s and women’s prisons, Dana Britton identifies the factors that influence the gendering of the American workplace, a process that often leaves women in lower-paying jobs with less prestige and responsibility.In interviews with dozens of male and female officers in five prisons, Britton explains how gender shapes their day-to-day work experiences. Combining criminology, penology, and feminist theory, she offers a radical new argument for the persistence of gender inequality in prisons and other organizations. At Work in the Iron Cage demonstrates the importance of the prison as a site of gender relations as well as social control.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCorrectional personnelxTraining ofzUnited States. 0aCorrectional personnelzUnited States. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzUnited States. 0aInmate guardszUnited States. 0aPrisonszUnited StatesxOfficials and employees. 0aPrisonszUnited States. 0aWomen correctional personnelzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aCage.  aIron.  aWork.  acontrol.  ademonstrates.  agender.  aimportance.  aprison.  arelations.  asite.  asocial.  awell.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081479883640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814723081423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814723081/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK